title: For Sale/Trade:  Lee Enfield .303 Rifle, Scope, Magazines, and Ammo
location: Near Faribault - South of Twin Cities -, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Update:  Sale Pending for 10-18-2014.  

For sale is a sporterized, SMLE, Number 1, Mark 3, Lee Enfield rifle in .303.  

The rifle is bolt action with a strong return spring.  It comes with a 3 – 9x40, wideview, fully coated, Simmons scope with lens covers on a Weaver mount.  

I like rifles that have a sense of history to them and the Lee Enfield fits that bill.  I wanted to know what it felt like to fire an Enfield (even a sporterized version) and how accurate they were.  I wasn’t disappointed.  The .303 cartridge has enough punch to knock down anything in North America (apparently Africa, Antarctica, India, Korea, and many more places too) that you would need to.  

Being a fan of such British war films as Breaker Morant, Immortal Sergeant, The Lost Patrol, The Desert Rats, A Bridge Too Far, Kelley’s Heroes, Cast a Giant Shadow, The Lighthorsemen, Legends of the Fall (chick flick, still solid fight scenes though), and Zulu Dawn I had to buy an Enfield and spend some time at the range with it.  

So what about this particular rifle? I put ~100-rounds through it.  I fired it for both speed and accuracy.  It never had a failure to fire or failure to eject and the rounds all struck where they should – any lack of accuracy is my fault and not the rifles.  

The rifle comes with two magazines and both were test fired with no issues.  

The rifle is not new.  The rifle is not pretty.  The rifle will most likely still be functional long after I am not.  

If you’re looking for a dependable bolt action rifle to drop furry critters in North America this may be your thing.  

Rifle will come with 40-rounds of factory .303 ammo.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin 444 - Early Model
postcontent: Marlin 444 in excellent condition. No scratches, chips, dents, rust or marks. The blueing is still dark and uniform and the stock is Walnut with a hand rubbed oil-finish. It is somewhere between a 1968 and 1970 version depending on what system you look at for the Serial # codes. It was purchased new by a family member and given to me in 1972 for my 21st birthday. I'm not able to hunt any more myself, there is no one in my family to pass it down to and I have no place to display the rifle ... so I hate it but away it goes.
